<DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
   <title> The align-content Property </title>
   <style type="text/css">
      .container {
         display: flex;
         flex-wrap: wrap;
         align-content: stretch;
         background: blue;
         padding: 5px;
         height: 400px;
      }
      .container > div {
         background: yellow;
         width: 100px;
         line-height: 80px;
         text-align: center;
         margin: 5px;
      }
   </style>
</head>
<body>
   <p> Since the <b>align-content</b> property does not work when there is only one line of flex items, we need to set the <b>flex-wrap: wrap</b> CSS declaration to wrap the flex items onto multiple lines. </p>
   <div class="container">
      <div> 1 </div>
      <div> 2 </div>
      <div> 3 </div>
      <div> 4 </div>
      <div> 5 </div>
      <div> 6 </div>
      <div> 7 </div>
      <div> 8 </div>
      <div> 9 </div>
   </div>
   <p> <b>align-content</b> valid values: </p>
   <ul>
      <li><b>stretch</b>: flex items are stretched to take the remaining space </li>
      <li><b>flex-start</b>: packs items to the start of the flex container's cross start </li>
      <li><b>flex-end</b>: packs items to the start of the flex container's cross end </li>
      <li><b>center</b>: packs items to the center toward the center of the alignment of the cross axis </li>
      <li><b>space-between</b>: distributes flex items evenly within the alignment of the cross axis; the space between adjacent (any two) items is equal; the first line is at the start of the cross axis and the last is at the end </li>
      <li><b>space-around</b>: distributes flex items evenly within the alignment of the cross axis with equal space around each line </li>
   </ul>
</body>
</html>